+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01GtPcT5Q692Eob4Gmb2sc8r","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Autopilot Design Decisions\n\n**Q1: Module structure?**\n→ Choosing: **Option B — Split into multiple files** (types.ts, document-store.ts, merge.ts, index.ts)\nReasoning: The merge logic is complex enough to warrant its own file. Types are reused across modules. Keeps each file focused and testable. Not over-engineered since we have 3 distinct concerns (types, store, merge).\n\n**Q2: Internal data model for branches?**\n→ Choosing: **Map<branchName, Map<docId, DocumentRecord>>** where DocumentRecord contains versions array and a deleted flag.\nReasoning: Each branch needs independent state. Storing per-branch document maps allows O(1) branch switching and clean isolation. Deep cloning at branch creation captures the snapshot.\n\n**Q3: How to track branch divergence points for three-way merge?**\n→ Choosing: **Snapshot-at-fork approach** — when creating a branch, store a deep clone of the source branch's state as the \"common ancestor\" for that branch pair.\nReasoning: This is simpler than tracking commit DAGs. We store `forkPoints: Map<string, Map<string, Map<docId, content>>>` mapping `childBranch -> parentBranch -> docSnapshots`. This gives us the base state for three-way merge without needing a full commit graph.\n\n**Q4: Three-way merge algorithm?**\n→ Choosing: **Recursive field-by-field comparison** with dot-path tracking.\nReasoning: Compare base vs ours, base vs theirs at each field. If only one side changed, take that change. If both changed to same value, no conflict. If both changed to different values, conflict. Recurse into nested objects. For non-object fields (arrays, primitives), treat as atomic values.\n\n**Q5: How to handle document creation/deletion in merge?**\n→ Choosing: **Treat as field-level changes** — document created on one branch = all fields are \"theirs\" changes (auto-merge). Document deleted on one branch = if other branch didn't modify it, accept deletion; if other branch modified it, conflict.\nReasoning: Keeps the merge logic consistent. Creation on one side with no corresponding doc on the other is clean. Deletion conflicts only when both sides touched the doc.\n\n**Q6: Version ID generation?**\n→ Choosing: **Simple incrementing counter** with a prefix (e.g., `v1`, `v2`, etc.) shared across the entire store.\nReasoning: UUIDs are overkill for in-memory use. A monotonic counter ensures uniqueness and ordering. Simple and deterministic for testing.\n\n**Q7: Deep cloning strategy?**\n→ Choosing: **`structuredClone`** (available in Node.js 17+ and we target ES2022).\nReasoning: Built-in, handles nested objects and arrays correctly, no dependencies needed. More robust than JSON.parse(JSON.stringify()) for edge cases.\n\nNow let me write the design document and then implement."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":330,"cache_read_input_tokens":22614,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":330,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"57ab5114-d69f-4d18-bbfc-b60090973393","uuid":"058cc67d-94f6-4530-9ff1-1e5ad862b403"}
